Welcome back to Wall Power. I=E2=80=99m Marion
Maneker.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

With so many folks in Mexico City, I wanted to look at the latest Gabriel O=
rozco retrospective that just opened at the Museo Jumex. Then I noticed tha=
t the Royal Academy in London has a new show about Brazilian modernism. So =
I thought I would examine both briefly for a fresh perspective. Julie Davic=
h, our roving art market correspondent, also
stopped by the RxArt gala and Salon Art + Design=E2=80=99s new pop-up; she =
also spent some time at the Hill Art Foundation=E2=80=99s group show curate=
d by Hilton Als.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But first, some breaking news=E2=80=A6

* Artsy layoffs: Earlier this morning, online art brokerage Artsy laid off =
all 15 employees on the secondary-market sales team. The only silver lining=
: They were allowed to keep their laptops.

It appears the company, whose main business is a marketplace that allows ga=
lleries to sell online, had to make a choice about where to invest its reso=
urces. =E2=80=9CProduct and tech investments are needed to successfully sca=
le this business,=E2=80=9D the secondary sales
team was told, =E2=80=9Cand at this point in time we need to focus on impro=
ving our partner experience and growing the core marketplace.=E2=80=9D Arts=
y=E2=80=99s press team did not immediately respond to my emails, texts, or =
phone calls for comment.

Now, here=E2=80=99s Julie=E2=80=A6

Julie Brener Davich
Julie Brener Davich

* RxArt=E2=80=99s starry
night: On Wednesday night, I swung by The Pool for the 25th anniversary gal=
a of RxArt, the nonprofit founded by Diane Brown to bring art into pediatri=
c hospitals. The therapeutic value of art=E2=80=94like Takashi Murakami flo=
wers in a C.T. scan room, or a corridor adorned with Nicolas Party=E2=80=99=
s colorful cotton-candy trees=E2=80=94is now widely acknowledged, but that =
wasn=E2=80=99t always the case. In its early days, the organization receive=
d
support from Agnes Gund, whom Brown thanked for her =E2=80=9Cencouragement =
when everyone else told me I was crazy.=E2=80=9D Today, RxArt boasts 66 pro=
jects with 96 artists in 44 hospitals in 27 cities.

Rx Art

Photo: Billy Farrell/BFA.com

* Brown credited the artworks she has placed with bringing smiles to the fa=
ces of young patients, or at least some much-needed distraction, and thanke=
d the artists who are =E2=80=9Cthe backbone of RxArt.=E2=80=9D Indeed, I=E2=
=80=99ve never been in a single room with as many big-name artists as I was=
 on that night: Eli Sudbrack, Will Cotton, Michele Oka Doner, Marcel Dzama,=
 Shara Hughes, Jeff Koons, Ryan
McGinley, and Rob Pruitt, to name just a few. Timothy Greenfield-Sanders co=
mmemorated the occasion with a group photo (see above).

On display at the gala were several limited editions available for sale ( h=
ttps://www.rxart.org/prints?page=3D2&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBER=
S+%282%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F7%2F25%29&=
utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42a=
bd12a ) to support RxArt, including prints by Loie Hollowell, Ewa Juszkiewi=
cz, Hilary Pecis, and this
year=E2=80=99s contributing artist, Ed Ruscha. The event also marked the ar=
rival of Katie Hollander as the organization=E2=80=99s new director, a role=
 that=E2=80=99s been vacant since Megan Skidmore departed two years ago to =
join Powerhouse Arts. (Previously, Hollander was the chief development offi=
cer at the Jewish Museum.) RxArt=E2=80=99s future projects include Mickalen=
e Thomas in South Brooklyn; Jonas Wood in Boston; and Alexis
Rockman in Cincinnati.

* Salon Art + Design=E2=80=99s Bergdorf pop-up: Bergdorf Goodman=E2=80=99s =
seventh floor, a jewel box of designer homewares, now also boasts a small p=
op-up design fair from Salon Art + Design, the fair that takes place every =
autumn at the Park Avenue Armory. Six galleries who participated in the fai=
r=E2=80=99s most recent edition each have an alcove in the hallway that run=
s the length of the store, painted with a different limewash by Color Ateli=
er. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve been getting a lot of people who don=E2=80=99t n=
ormally
come,=E2=80=9D said Bergdorf Goodman sales rep Kelly Fraser, =E2=80=9Clike =
Instagrammers.=E2=80=9D

If you go, go for the ceramics. =E2=80=9CCeramics are having a moment,=E2=
=80=9D Fraser told me. Liz O=E2=80=99Brien gallery is featuring black and w=
hite ceramics from Bill Hudnut, Isobel Egan, Zachary Zimmerman, and=E2=80=
=94my favorite=E2=80=94several brutalist vessels from R.A. Pesce priced fro=
m $1,750 to $6,000. Verso is also showing ceramics, but their hero piece is
the serpentine lavender powdercoat chair by Matthew Day Jackson, available =
for $14,250 in an edition of 10, plus two artist=E2=80=99s proofs. The othe=
r participating galleries are J. Lohmann, Room 57, Onishi, and Galerie Gabr=
iel. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s early days,=E2=80=9D said Fraser, =E2=80=9Cbut w=
e=E2=80=99ve sold a lot.=E2=80=9D The pop-up is on view until April 13.

=E2=80=8A

The Writing=E2=80=99s on the Wall
---------------------------

=E2=80=9CWe handed over the space and the collection to Hilton,=E2=80=9D Hi=
ll Art Foundation
executive director Sarah Needham told me this week, referring to the writer=
 and critic Hilton Als. Apparently, Als was supposed to put together a solo=
 presentation of photographs by Robert Bergman, =E2=80=9Cbut he ended up go=
ing in a different direction,=E2=80=9D Needham laughed.

The resulting group exhibition, on view through March 29, is titled The Wri=
ting=E2=80=99s on the Wall: Language and Silence in Visual Arts, and focuse=
s
on themes of writing and erasure. Als brought together works from the found=
ation=E2=80=99s founders, J. Tomilson and Janine Hill, with loans from gall=
eries and a few works from his own personal collection. Needham recalled ho=
w Als showed up with artworks in his backpack the day before the show opene=
d=E2=80=94like Larry Wolhandler=E2=80=99s small bronze bust of James Baldwi=
n=E2=80=94and just started physically placing pieces around the Peter
Marino=E2=80=93designed space. =E2=80=9CMeasurements are not really his thi=
ng,=E2=80=9D she conceded.

Some of the artworks, like the Cy Twombly chalkboard painting and the Vija =
Celmins pink eraser sculpture, fit clearly into the show=E2=80=99s theme of=
 =E2=80=9Clanguage itself [as] a primary visual medium,=E2=80=9D as Holland=
 Cotter put it in The New York Times. Others require deeper reflection, lik=
e Jennie C. Jones=E2=80=99s red wall installation
featuring an acoustic panel. All three works come from the Hills, who are k=
nown for acquiring in four categories: Renaissance and Baroque bronzes, Old=
 Masters, modern art, and contemporary art, including one of the largest, i=
f not the largest, collection of works by Christopher Wool. (The Hills open=
ed the foundation in 2019 as a public exhibition and education space; it al=
so happens to be a great tax write-off.)

In addition to drawing from the foundation=E2=80=99s
holdings, Als called in loans of specific works he knew he wanted to includ=
e in the show, like Ellen Gallagher=E2=80=99s DeLuxe, a grid of 60 prints b=
ased on vintage advertisements from African American magazines. Other works=
 he found by telephoning galleries and asking if they had any artists that =
incorporate language. That led him to Rachel Harrison=E2=80=99s 2021 sculpt=
ure with a found typewriter, Hermes, from Greene Naftali gallery, and Ina
Archer=E2=80=99s 2024 video installation Black Black Moonlight: A Minstrel =
Show, from Microscope Gallery. Whether there was a method to Als=E2=80=99s =
madness, or madness to his method, it worked.

The next show at the Hill Art Foundation, opening in May, is curated by art=
ist Sam Moyer. It will feature works of hers from the Hills=E2=80=99 collec=
tion, as well as others=E2=80=99 works from the collection that speak to he=
r. Meanwhile, Als also curated an Alice Neel
exhibition ( http://online.victoria-miro.com/alice-neel-london-2025/?utm_ca=
mpaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power=
+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcust=
omer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) at Victoria Miro gallery, which is =
on view through March 8.

Okay, I=E2=80=99m back=E2=80=A6

